eden","1315–Male":"1315–Overleden","1320–Female":"1320–Overleden","1315":"1315","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Wales":"Wales"},"en":{"1345–1392":"1345–1392","1345–Female":"1345–Deceased","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1315–Male":"1315–Deceased","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","1315":"1315","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ithel","type":"LAST","meanings":["A Welsh name derived from the Greek, signifying 'blooming luxuriantly, flourishing, rich.'. It is from Ithel that we have first the name Ap-Ithel, then by corruption, Bithell and Bethell."],"variants":[{"name":"Bithell","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Bethel  ."]},{"name":"Bethell","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Bethel  ."]}]},{"name":"Vychan","type":"LAST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gwilim","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Gwillym","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gwilim ap Ithel Vychan was born in 1345, in Wales, his father, Ithel ap Madog, was 31 and his mother, ap Madog, was 26. He had at least 1 son with ap Ithel Vychan. He died in 1392, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1345–1392":"1345–1392","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1315":"1315","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"1345–1392":"1345–1392","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1315–Male":"1315–Kuollut","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Wales":"Wales"},"fr":{"1345–1392":"1345–1392","1345–Female":"1345–Décédée","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1360–Male":"1360–Décédé","1315–Male":"1315–Décédé","1320–Female":"1320–Décédée","1315":"1315","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Wales":"Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Gwilim ap Ithel Vychan est né en 1345, à Galles, son père, Ithel ap Madog, avait 31 ans et sa mère, ap Madog, avait 26 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec ap Ithel Vychan. Il est décédé en 1392, à l’âge de 47 ans."},"de":{"1345–1392":"1345–1392","1345–Female":"1345–Verstorben","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1360–Male":"1360–Verstorben","1315–Male":"1315–Verstorben","1320–Female":"1320–Verstorben","1315":"1315","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","Wales":"Wales","lifeSummary":"Als Gwilim ap Ithel Vychan 1345 in Wales geboren wurde, war sein Vater Ithel ap Madog 31 und seine Mutter ap Madog 26. Er hatte mit ap Ithel Vychan mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb 1392 im Alter von 47 Jahren."},"ht":{"1345–1392":"1345–1392","1345–Female":"1345–Desede","1330–1392":"1330–1392","1360–Male":"1360–Desede","1315–Male":"1315–Desede","1320–Female":"1320–Desede","1315":"1315","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","136